AGU OS 2022

The influence of recent major wildfires on ENSO

J. Fasullo, N. Rosenbloom, and R. Buchholz

Major wildfire seasons in recent years include the exceptional fire outbreaks in Eurasia and North America in 2017 and 2018, and in the Amazon and Australia from 2019 through 2020. These events are known to inject considerable biomass and particulate organic matter into the atmosphere, absorbing solar radiation, reflecting it to space, and altering the optical properties of clouds on regional scales. But are these effects strong enough to influence the occurrence of the El Niño / Southern Oscillation (ENSO)?

In this work, simulation ensembles using the Community Earth System Model Version 2 (CESM2) are produced to estimate the impact of recent wildfires on the evolution of ENSO. It is found that recent fires altered the inter-hemispheric radiative imbalance, thereby displacing the ITCZ into the opposing hemisphere. While a distinct set of mechanisms characterizes the cooling response to wildfires, the associated ITCZ shift is consistent with that seen following major volcanic eruptions in that it shifts away from the cooled hemisphere in order to enhance cross equatorial transports of dry static energy and reduce inter-hemispheric thermal contrasts. In turn, the ITCZ shift increases the probability of El Niño for northern hemisphere fires and La Niña for southern hemisphere fires. The role of tropical fires in ENSO is also explored.--------------------

Hi John,

The ENSO climatology of monthly fire emissions have been created and are here:
"El Niño" - /glade/work/buchholz/emis/gfed_climatology/elnino
"La Niña" - /glade/work/buchholz/emis/gfed_climatology/lanina

To summarize, the averages are of:
El Niño  Yr0: 1997, 2009, 2015
              Yr1: 1998, 2010, 2016
              Yr2: 1999, 2011, 2017
La Niña Yr0: 1998, 2007, 2010
              Yr1: 1999, 2008, 2011
              Yr2: 2000, 2009, 2012

I have arbitrarily created both files starting at 2000. The emissions look different to the 2000-2018 climatology, e.g.


Let me know if you have any questions or find any issues with the files.
